	   <a name=103516756575825></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f103516756575825><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=item.html?item=3693&mid=103516756575825>RE: Haste</a> <a id=fs8 href=item.html?item=3693&mid=103516756575825#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=186413><span id= >eonx</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>3 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sun, Oct 20th 10:51 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Haste does not modify your delay. It modifies the number of attacks you attempt in a given time.<br><br>For instance, a 20 delay weapon equates to a delay of 2.0 seconds inbetween attack attempts. Therefore, you can attempt 30 attacks in one minute.<br><br>Having an FBSS, being 21% haste, gives you 30 x 1.21 = 36.3 attacks per minute. If you convert that back into a delay, you come up with 1.6529 seconds, or a delay of 16.529.<br><br>However, if you tried to simply decrease the delay, you'd end up with an incorrect answer. Observe: 2.0 seconds - ( 2.0 x 0.21 ) = 1.58 seconds, or a delay of 15.8.<br><br>The steps to attain the correct result can be simplied and expressed as:<br>new_delay = old_delay x ( 1 / ( 1 + haste_expressed_as_a_decimal ) )<br><br>An example of the formula:<br>16.529 = 20 x ( 1 / ( 1 + 0.21 ) )<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Sun Oct 20 22:39:34 2002</em><br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
	   </form></table><ul>

